baseline, 142.5 ± 1.7° at Step 1, 152.1 ± 1.8° at Step 2, 165.8 ± 1.9° at Step 
3, and 166.0 ± 1.4° at Step 4); this was followed by an enhanced COP. Gradually, 
gait features also improved. Additionally, the AMP score (5 at baseline to 29 at 
Step 4) and K-level (K0 at baseline to K3 at Step 4) increased after ATAD. Along 
with these improvements, the SF-36 score also improved.
CONCLUSIONS: ATAD could be beneficial for transtibial amputees by relieving knee 
contractures and improving gait.

